               <p>489. <persName id="def1-489-18580405" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-489-18580405" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-489-18580405" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-489-18580405" type="given" value="MARIA"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">MARIA SMITH</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18580405-489-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18580405-489-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="royalOffences"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18580405-489-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="coiningOffences"></interp> for a like offence.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MESSRS. THOMPSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">LAXTON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18580405-name-739" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18580405-name-739" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18580405-name-739" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18580405-name-739" type="given" value="EMILY"></interp>EMILY SMITH</persName>
                  </hi>. My father is a corn chandler at Knight's Place, Wands<lb></lb>worth. On 2d March, about 12 o'clock in the day, the prisoner came for a pint of beans; it came to 2 1/4 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—she gave me a half crown; it bent very easily, and I told her I thought it was bad, and she had better take it back—shesaid she should not take it back, her husband must take it back, as he had taken it from his master this morning—I gave it to my father.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18580405-name-740" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18580405-name-740" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18580405-name-740" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18580405-name-740" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE SMITH</persName>
                  </hi>. My daughter gave me this coin (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>)—I fold the prisoner it was not good, and asked her where she got it—she said her hus<lb></lb>band took it for his work in the market—I asked her name; she said, "Neale," or "O'Neale," and pretended to cry; I do not know whether it was real—I sent her to fetch her husband, and she went away—I followed her to the soup kitchen, Vauxhall Wharf, and called a policeman—She said, "Do forgive me, I know I have done wrong; do not take me to the station"—I said, "Where did you get it?" she said, "I dare not tell you"—I said, "Where do you live?" she said, "In the Mint"—on the road, she said that she was hungry and dry, and a gentleman gave it to her to get something—Isaid, "It is strange that you should go to a corn chandler's shop to get peas,"and that if she had gone tcr a baker's, it would have been more feasible—she said that she did not know what she was doing.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When she said, "Forgive me," did not she say, "I did not know it was a bad one; I had it given to me this morning?" <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I will not swear she did not.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18580405-name-741" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18580405-name-741" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18580405-name-741" type="surname" value="MEEKING"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18580405-name-741" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY MEEKING</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Policeman, L</hi> 143). Mr. Smith pointed out the prisoner to me, and I followed her from Vauxhall Wharf, and overtook her in Tyer Street—I said, "Where did you get the half crown?"—she said that some one gave it to her—I asked her who; she said she durst not tell me—I asked her what made her so frightened, when she was told that it was bad—she said, "Because I knew I was doing wrong"—she refused her name and address—Isaid, "You must have known it was bad"—she said, "No; a man gave it to me opposite"—she afterwards srtid that she lived in Lambeth Walk—I said, "I know you do not live anywhere over there"—she said she dare not tell me where she lived—she aftehwards said that she lived in the, Borough, in lodging houses, whenever she got 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. to pay for a lodging, and that she had taken the half crown for a bad purpose—this was all in answer to questions</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185804050188"></xptr>
               <p>of mine.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Was not she crying? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> She began to cry after<lb></lb>wards.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18580405-name-742" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18580405-name-742" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18580405-name-742" type="surname" value="WEBSTER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18580405-name-742" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM WEBSTER</persName>
                  </hi>. This half crown is counterfeit.</p>
